'''Bottle cutting''' is an activity in which a person cuts a [[bottle]] using one of a variety of techniques, to create a new product. Techniques can include [[saw]]ing or using [[Hot-wire foam cutter|hot wire]]. Around the late 1950s and early 1960s, some [[restaurant]]s began making [[List of glassware|glasses]] by cutting [[wine bottle]]s. In the late 1960s and early 1970s, bottle cutting kits started to appear on the market.<ref>http://www.ephremsbottleworks.com/</ref> By 1972, the technique had "caught on like wildfire"<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TNQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA190&dq=%22Bottle+cutting%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cFv5TujiC4mJmQW6hf2jAg&ved=0CGgQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22Bottle%20cutting%22&f=false | title=Popular Mechanics | date=November 1972 | accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> and was later described as a [[fad]] of the previous decade in 1983.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0n0gAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Bottle+cutting%22&dq=%22Bottle+cutting%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=UFr5TpqVK4eGmQWduoSDAg&ved=0CGAQ6AEwBTgK | title=Mechanix illustrated , Volume 79, Issues 656-661 | publisher=CBS Publications | year=1983 | accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> The final step in bottle cutting is [[polishing]], because no matter how carefully one cuts a bottle, the edges will be rough.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aP9GAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Bottle+cutting%22&dq=%22Bottle+cutting%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NVn5ToWcOs3DmQXz1rGXAg&ved=0CHEQ6AEwCQ | title=Re/uses: 2133 ways to recycle and reuse the things you ordinarily throw away | accessdate=December 27, 2011 | author=Jabs, Carolyn | pages=83}}</ref>
