[[Image:Ingannati.jpg|right|thumb|Cover to the Italian comedy of intrigue, ''[[The Deceived Ones]]'' ({{lang-it|Gl'ingannati}}, [[1531 in literature|1531]]).]] The '''comedy of intrigue''', also known as the '''comedy of situation''', is a [[Literary genre|genre]] of [[comedy]] in which [[Action (philosophy)|dramatic action]] is prioritised over the development of [[Character (arts)|character]], complicated strategems and conspiracies drive the plot, and [[Farce|farcical humour]] and contrived or ridiculous dramatic situations are often employed.<ref>Merriam-Webster (1995, 261) and Pavis (1998, 65).</ref> Characterisation tends to be defined only vaguely and the plot gives the illusion of dynamic, constant movement.<ref>Pavis (1998, 65).</ref> The German philosopher [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]] argued that characters pursue their aims in such comedies via the use of [[deception]].<ref>Paolucci (1978, 101).</ref> The genre was first developed in the [[Theatre of ancient Rome|theatre of classical Rome]] by [[Plautus]] and [[Terence]].<ref>Law (2011, 120).</ref> Examples of comedies of intrigue include [[Niccolò Machiavelli|Niccolò Machiavelli's]] ''[[The Mandrake]]'' (1524), the [[Anonymous work|anonymous]] Italian play ''[[The Deceived Ones]]'' (1531), [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'' (c. 1596) and "[[Much Ado About Nothing]]", [[Thomas Heywood]]'s ''[[The Wise Woman of Hoxton]]'' (c. 1604), [[Molière]]'s ''[[Scapin the Schemer]]'' (1671), and the plays of [[Aphra Behn]] and [[Thomas D'Urfey]].<ref>Cohn (1998, 234), Hochman (1984, 251), and Pavis (1998, 65).</ref>
==See also== * [[Situation comedy]] * [[Comedy of humours]] * [[Comedy of manners]]
