The '''Glossolalia debate''' ({{lang-no|Tungetaledebatten}}) was a literary debate on [[modernist poetry]] in Norway in the 1950s. The debate started with [[Arnulf Øverland]]'s nationwide touring with the speech ''Tungetale fra Parnasset'' ({{lang-en|[[Glossolalia]] from the Parnassus}}) in 1953, characterizing modernist literature as [[Babbling|babble]] and [[nonsense]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Arnulf Øverland |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Willy |last=Dahl |authorlink=Willy Dahl |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Arnulf_Øverland/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> His talk was published in ''[[Arbeiderbladet]]'' in 1954, and resulted in a fierce debate. Among the defenders of modernist poetry were [[Odd Solumsmoen]], [[Olav Dalgard]] and [[Paal Brekke]],<ref name=dahl3>{{cite book |title=Tid og tekst 1935-1972 |series=Norges litteratur |volume=3 |chapter=Tungetale-debatten |pages=157–159 |first=Willy |last=Dahl |authorlink=Willy Dahl |publisher=Aschehoug  |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian |year=1989 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Paal Brekke |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Øystein |last=Rottem |authorlink=Øystein Rottem |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Paal_Brekke/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> while poet and literary critic [[André Bjerke]] joined Øverland's criticism.<ref name=dahl3/>

The glossolalia debate was discussed in the literary magazine ''[[Profil (literary magazine)|Profil]]'' in 1968.<ref name=dahl3/>

