'''Ishikozume''' (Japanese 石子詰め) was a ritual method of execution performed in ancient Japan by the [[Yamabushi]], hermetic practitioners of the [[Shugendō]] religion. The ritual is characterized by waist high burial in earth followed by [[lapidation]] (death by stoning).<ref>{{ cite journal |last=Earhart |first=H. Byron |authorlink=H. Byron Earhart|date=August 1966 |title=Ishikozume Ritual Execution in Japanese Religion, Especially in Shugendō |journal=Numen |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=116–127 |doi=10.1163/156852766X00077 |jstor=3269418}}</ref>

