'''Satya Pir''' ({{lang-bn|সত্যপীর}}) is a belief system found in [[Bengal]] created by the fusion of [[Islam]] and local religions. Experts maintain that the Muslim ''Satya Pir'' and the [[Hindu]] [[Satyanarayan Puja]] essentially represent the same beliefs and rituals.<ref name=pedia>{{cite web|last1=Karim|first1=Abdul|title=Satya Pir|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Satya_Pir|website=Banglapedia|accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref>
A century ago in Bengal, the ritual called, pujah was mainly performed by Hindu women and was interchangeably called Satya pir Pujah or Satya Narayan pujah.

According to the author, Dwijendra Nath Neogi, some  Muslims  at that time also performed the pujah. The author gives alternate theories as to how Pir and Narayan got associated. In one theory, he proposes that Brahmins during the Islamic era  in Bengal changed Narayan into Pir in order for the Muslims to believe that they were worshipping an Islamic saint. The other theory says the worship started as that of a Muslim saint or Pir and later the Pir was changed into Narayan.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Neogi|first1=Dwijendra Nath|title=Sacred Tales of India|date=1916|publisher=MacMillan & Company|location=London , UK|pages=95–100|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=NU4qAAAAYAAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA1&dq=satya+pir+narayan+ritual&ots=llvGX0F3PX&sig=epDPptySUj2pLIVXkQzosCkjsOU#v=onepage&q=pir&f=false|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> 

In folklores, Narayan and Pir get mixed such as one supplicant will address him as Satya Narayana, implying that he is an avatar of Krishna, while another one in a different tale will be told that Satya Pir has just come from Mecca, which would make him Muslim.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wells|first1=Darla|title=Fabulous Females and Peerless Pirs: Tales of Mad Adventure in Old Benga|journal=Journal of Folklore Research Reviews,  -|date=2006|url=http://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/jfrr/article/view/2405/2281}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Uddin|first1=S|last2=Raj|first2=S|last3=Harman|first3=W|title=Dealing with Deities: The Ritual Vow in South Asia - Chapter 6 In  the company of Pirs: Making vows, receiving favors at Bangladeshi Sufi Shrines -|date=2006|publisher=State University of New York, Albany , NY, USA|location=Albany, NY, USA|isbn=0-7914-6707-4|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=h80yOTwlAUcC&oi=fnd&pg=PA87&dq=satya+pir+narayan&ots=DmTlx8Ma7W&sig=pnHWV73SquPuT1OkcGOVolWX7WU#v=onepage&q=satya%20pir%20narayan&f=false}}</ref>

In Orissa, the state adjacent to Bengal,  Sufism gained popularity and led to the emergence of the Satya-Pir tradition. Even today Hindus worship Satyanarayan and pir together.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kanungo|first1=P|title=Hindutva's Entry into a 'Hindu Province': Early Years of RSS in Orissa|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|date=2003|volume=38|issue=31 (Aug. 2-8, 2003), pp. 3293-3303, No. 31 (Aug. 2-8, 2003),|pages=3295|jstor=4413860}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Puniyani|first1=Ed.: Ram|title=Religion, power & violence : expression of politics in contemporary times|date=2005|publisher=Sage|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-7619-3338-7|pages=21, 117–118|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=ioyHAwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA108&dq=%22satya+pir%22+merchant&ots=STKXVIg64H&sig=SBo4qC92VP6ozd6zY1hz-XZZi7g#v=onepage&q=%22satya%20pir%22&f=false|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref>

Satya pir is worshipped by some Buddhists in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barua|first1=Dilip Kumar|title=A case study in the popular Buddhist belief in Bangladesh|journal=Society for the Study of Pali and Buddhist Culture|page=96|url=http://enlight.lib.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-AN/an147362.pdf}}</ref>

